segments.text: Let me just correct one thing.
I was talking about the preferred growth sketch.
The preferred growth sketch was what the planning department came up with in November of 1976, and what the city council approved in March of 1977 was entitled the San Antonio
the San Antonio growth sketch.
And that was the thing that was officially approved by city council.
So what we're talking about is the whole growth study project that was initiated during Cipriano Guerra's tenure as director of planning.
It's important also to realize that several very significant things happened during this period of time which caused San Antonio's more recent planning activities to happen.
The first of which is that the council that was elected in 1975, in April of 1975, took office on
the 1st of May, 1975, was the council for the first time that the Good Government League did not dominate.
There were only three of the nine council members were Good Government League people.
The mayor, Mayor Cockrell, Henry Cisneros, who was elected for the first time in 1975,
and Phil Pendous were the three council members.
The rest were members of the independent team.
The significant thing about that is that one of the members of the independent team was a man by the name of Glenn Hartman.
And Hartman was a person who came out of civil service working for the Air Force and was basically a strategic planner.
He wasn't a land planner or a city planner,
He was probably as much as anyone responsible for getting the city of San Antonio to start thinking seriously about a plan again.
What Hartman did was he read Article 9 of the city charter and asked the question, why doesn't the city of San Antonio have a plan when the charter says thou shall have a plan?
And he worked with
a retired colonel by the name of Bill Dodds, D-O-D-D-S, to research what were the reasons, particularly the structural reasons, which kept the city of San Antonio from developing a plan.
Everybody recognized we didn't have a plan.
Everybody recognized that the Charter said you would have one.
The question was why we didn't.
It appears from the
chronology of planning and planters in San Antonio so far that San Antonio could be looked at as a graveyard for planters.
You have to explain.
I don't understand what you mean.
Well, their tenure was very short.
And they were usually run out of town or run out of the state.
Well, that's not true.
That only happened.
That happened, the only one that was kind of run off because of a specific planning activity was Charles Stromberg.
Davis, it was a, well, Davis was a combination, no, Davis, I think, was a combination of his personality and planning.
And, you know, you know Ed as well as I do, and he had a very strong personality.
Ed Davis resigned.
He wasn't fired.
And he resigned because of
some things that he strongly believed in.
So I don't think it's fair to characterize San Antonio as a graveyard for planning.
Well, I think there is a certain amount of truth in it, regardless of... Well, I just disagree totally with that.
Why do you disagree?
I know I can't.
You know, I think that there were some people that... Well, first of all, let me back up and say
First of all, I don't think the community knew what planning was.
And the community didn't really think that the city should be involved in planning.
And there were some people that were strongly opposed to city staff planners doing any planning.
But I don't think that's unlike many other cities go through a period of time where people don't appreciate or understand
the value of planning.
And I think that was true in San Antonio during that period of planning.
It did have the result after Davis left and after Stromberg was fired of many of those people that Davis attracted to the planning department got disillusioned and left.
And they're spread all across the country right now.
And that's very unfortunate because Davis was able to, as I said, attract
Well, this is part of why I mentioned that characterization.
Well, but I still don't like the statement that it was a graveyard.
Well, I'm sure you don't like it.
Okay, well, let's put a mush on.
Okay, then, the other point I was going to make about these factors that contributed to the current, to the late 1970s planning effort is that

One of the things that came out of the Hartman-Dodd study was the fact that the then Planning and Zoning Commission really was spending all of its time hearing zoning cases and approving subdivision plots and really had no time to do planning.
So again, for the second time, the city council in March of 1976
officially split the Planning and Zoning Commission in two commissions.

The Zoning Commission, which was charged with all the zoning, and the Planning Commission, which was specifically charged with engaging in an active effort to come up with a plan for the city of San Antonio.
And to this day, we still have two commissions in San Antonio.
Did Hartman
Stick around to make sure that the Planning Commission would attend to its charge.
Yes.
Hartman was around.
He was first elected in 1975, was re-elected in 77, and may have even been, let's see, 79.
No, he was out by 79.
But what he did, he was around for four years, almost four years, three and a half years.
And not only did he keep his interest in planning and be very supportive, but also he was responsible for getting Bill Dodds on the planning commission.
In other words, it was an attempt to not only create a planning commission, but to make sure that
at least a significant number of its members were people that had some appreciation for plant.

When we discussed earlier the split of the commission in the 61 to 63 period, I don't think that there were people on the commission during that period of time that really understood what it was to, what effort it would take
to do a plan and what role the commission had to play.
I think that was different by 1976.
I had met Hartman at one of the short courses that the AIP was giving during those days.
And I was very impressed with Hartman and with his knowledge of comprehensive planning and the need for it in San Antonio.
energy and commitment to the idea that San Antonio was going to have comprehensive planning.
Yeah, I think, again, if this project gets to the point where he's a person that should be talked to, Glenn has kind of changed a lot.
He's very bitter about government in San Antonio.
He's moved from San Antonio.
He now lives in Austin.
And he's head of some state agency that's in charge with all state buildings.

but he is definitely someone that probably should be talked to because he did play kind of a critical role in that 1975 through 77 period when there was a major effort to get the city to do a plan that the charter had called for all along.
And the other thing that happened
The third thing, we were just talking about some of the major things that are occurring here, was that in January of 1977, there was only the second major change in the charter since 1951.
And that change was to expand the number of city council members from 9 to 11 and to elect the council members by district rather than at large.
So, all of them?
All of them.
Well, except for the mayor.
The mayor runs citywide, but all ten council persons other than the mayor run from geographic districts.
So, on May 1st, 1977, we had basically a very different council in San Antonio.
We had a council made up of
people that represented geographic areas.

Many of those people were also people that were serving for the first time, many of whom had defeated incumbents that had been on the previous council and just had a whole different view of what San Antonio should be doing with respect to its growth and development.
So that was another major effect that
an environmental effect that had a major impact on San Antonio's effort in the late 1970s to develop the plan.
Guerra stepped down.
Well, basically what happened actually is in addition to the split of the Planning and Zoning Commission, the Planning Department was reconstituted

Sometime also in 1976 and community development was split off and again there was a department of planning per se and in June of 1976 Robert Hunter became director of planning and served for about a four year period of time.
And during his tenure as director of planning, most of the big battles and controversies about the plan and what it should be occurred.
And he departed, he resigned, I guess it was sometime in 1980, I don't recall when, under some pressure to do so.
I have firsthand knowledge of that.
Bob was in architecture at A&M.
Yes.
And has his degree in architecture.
Yes.

And I think that says a lot about his approach to planning, that he was very visually oriented and not very development process oriented, and probably didn't have a very good understanding of the role.
of the development community and how it can interface with public agencies.
And I think that he probably had to learn that.
Well, let me just say that.
Two things in response.
One is that I'm not necessarily sure it was just his architectural training.
Because I can name an architect that I know
who probably has as much insight in planning as anyone who's gone through professional planning and had experience.
I think we all can do that.
But I think part of the problem with Bob is that his whole orientation was public agency.
He had come to the planning department from the San Antonio Development Agency as their planning manager, and his
He was dealing with project planning and basically public sector planning there.
So he really had not worked a great deal with the private sector in terms of development.
So it probably was less his education and more his own personal feelings and his previous experiences.

and there was all kinds of politics involved in that also, but be that as it may, he in 76 became director of planning and one of his first tasks was the revival and getting something done about the growth sketch itself and as I said, that occurred
in March of 77 with the council approving the San Antonio grill sketch.
So basically, by March of 77, or just before the first new city council took office on May 1, new meaning the expanded, elected by district city council,
then there was a buy-off on the basic policies for developing a plan and a charge to develop a plan itself.
And that's where we were in the spring of 1977 and really the next three or four years.
What do you mean by a buy-off?
Well, I mean that the council had

bought off on some policies as embodied in the San Antonio growth sketch, that would serve as a basis for the planners and the planning commission to come up with a plan and had given, on a number of occasions, had given the charge to let's get a plan done.

And then as I said, then the Hunter era, a four-year period of time was a period of time during which there was, one might say, all hell broke loose in terms of major efforts to develop a plan and a lot of controversy about what the role of planning in San Antonio should be and how the community should grow over a period of time.
You want to ask a question, or what?
No, we were going on about Hunter, and then he was under some pressure to leave, and then after Hunter, what happened?
Oh, well, wait a minute.
You can't skip over Hunter.
I'm not skipping over anybody.
Well, let me... After...

After the San Antonio growth sketch had been approved in March of 1977, the effort then was how do we go from this to a plan to meet the requirements of the charter and to meet the desires of the then city council.

So that was largely the responsibility of the Planning Commission, which was separate at that time and chaired by Margaret Lexner, L-E-C-Z-N-A-R, and the Planning Department, which at that time was headed by Bob Hunter.
Kind of one of the first things that were done was to look at how one might organize the final product.
In other words, what would be contained
a master plan itself.

And as I said, one of the problems that San Antonio had is that Article 9 of the Charter, although saying thou shalt have a plan and specifying in some detail the legal effect of the plan, didn't really give much guidance as to what a plan should be.
So the planning department, in conjunction with the commission, but largely the staff of the planning department, came up with
an outline for a city plan which had five chapters.

And so they viewed it as a document which would contain five chapters, and chapter one being an introduction, chapter two being a summary, chapter three being what they were calling the plan basis, chapter four being the goals, objectives, and policies of the plan, and then chapter five dealing with implementation.
What they... Too bad they hadn't read Ken's book.
Well, that would have only confused them.
Oh, no.
So the... Now, the idea was this.
The idea was to focus the effort on Chapter 4.
Chapter 4 being the goals, the objectives, and the policies of the plan itself.
And in order to do that, it was necessary to develop...
a statement of goals.
And so what happened in this period of time, and most of this effort was occurring from mid-1977.
Well, actually, the big effort on Chapter 4 was an effort that took place during calendar year 1978.
And the idea was to deal with a set of goals and then to articulate those goals into objectives and further specify those objectives into a set of policies.
And so the planning department staff working with the commission came up with a number of different areas.
And I needn't go into all this, but the result was that in September of 1978, a draft of Chapter 4 was presented by the Planning Department staff to the Planning Commission.
And it was a very detailed document.
It contained 60 or so pages of lots of statements.
Basically, it was about 60 pages of goals, objectives, and policies dealing with major areas.
You deal with neighborhoods and conservation and all different kinds of things.
Well, that document, Chapter 4, really created a lot of controversy for a lot of different reasons.
One reason was
that many people, and after you read 60 pages of goals and objectives and policies, you're sure to find some that you don't like.
So most people just took exception to the detail and to a lot of the substantive statements in those goals.
In addition...
In addition, a lot of people felt that, well, if we're dealing with Chapter 4,
where are the other chapters, particularly where is chapter three which was entitled the plan basis and was to be all the substantiating information that would set the stage for chapter four.
So people were saying well this is out of context.
The commission felt strongly after dealing with this for several months and it was just an incredible amount of time going through these things, all kinds of public hearings
all kinds of dealing with citizens.
And finally, in March of 1979, the commission said, well, why don't we just pass it on to city council and let them tell us, let them provide us with some direction.
And essentially that's what the commission did.
It sent the whole thing to city council.
City council rejected it out of hand and said,
and provided some guidelines for how one might go about developing a document.
And in reaction to that in mid-79, going into late 79, the whole idea of thinking about what the plan would look like got restructured
And the idea was to come up with, to first deal with a planned basis, some very general overall goals, and the institutional settings and all of that.
And that was accomplished in a relatively short period of time.
Went back to city council, was approved sometime in 1980, I don't recall, when mid-1980, August of 1980,
And then that was the plan basis.
And then from that, we've had a series of specific plans, the land use plan, the transportation plan, and all of those have been accomplished.
Different elements of a comprehensive plan.
Yes.
So the council has then taken action on all of these elements?
Well, what's happened since that time, and again, we've got to get back to some of the change in directors, but the basic plan was approved, I think, in August of 1980.
And then since then, a number of different elements of the plan have been approved by
the city council.
In other words, the transportation major thoroughfare plan was originally approved in 1978 and has been revised since then.
The land use plan, which was a major effort of the city, was approved about two years ago, I think in about 1988.
I think it was 1983 it was approved, okay.

And then there have been some specific things like the Parks and Recreation Plan and a number of others that are also either functional or geographic elements of the plan have been approved, all under the umbrella of the basic plan as kind of the departure point.
I see.
Okay.
The plans that you mention in the book, I'm going to refer to them as elements of the comprehensive plan.
Well, that's what they are.
So we can keep our nomenclature consistent within the book.
I thought we were doing an interview.
I guess I'm confused.
No, go ahead.
I just, I knew it would happen.
I just got a notice here that Joe Esherick has achieved emeritus status, having a re-informer Berkeley.
So, all right.
The council has taken action on these various elements, some of them, element by element.
Do you think that they will be moving toward adopting the entire package of elements?
Well, there's no need to.
The way the process was set up is that they approve the basic framework first, and then the elements are approved as they're finished.
So they automatically become part of the overall document.
They have approved the framework.
Yes, that was the basic plan.
That was done in August of 1980.
And then let me just go back and explain that Hunter left sometime in 79.
And I don't recall.
I think it was late in 79 or very early in 1980.
And then Lou Fox, who was an assistant city.
I think we should say about Hunter that when Hunter left, he became planning director in Las Vegas.
No.
When Hunter left, he went to work for the Council of Governments in Reno.
Reno, yes.
Yes.
And as far as I know, he still did.
Yes, I think he still did.
When he left, Lou Fox, Louis J.
Fox, who's now city manager of San Antonio and at that time was assistant city manager, kind of became an interim planning director.
while they were looking for a new planning director.
What happened, it's kind of interesting that the city, because of some of the problems in the planning department over that period of time, 77 to 80, wanted to hire a strong administrator.
They weren't really concerned about hiring a planner.
They wanted to hire a strong administrator.
That resulted in sometime in 1980, and I don't recall when, late in the year or early 1981, hiring Roland Lozano as director of planning.
And he is still the director of planning in the city of San Antonio.
L-O-Z-A-N-O.
And in the meantime, Houston has hired a new city planning director who came from Southern Ohio.
Yes, that was a classmate of mine at school.
And he is proceeding with a new style of planning for Houston.
Yes, as his education taught him to do.
We'll see what comes of that.
So, where are we now?
We're right up to date on planning directors.
Well, yeah, in terms of planning directors, we are.
What is the style of your current planning director?
Well, Roland's more of an administrator.
I mean, he was hired specifically as an administrator as opposed to...
He is not a planner.
He's had no experience and no education in planning.
He is, and he has been a...

uh i think he's got an mpa and he has been a manager of various departments and city government so he's just in as a manager okay let's talk a minute about planning staff who are professional planters and who have made contributions to planning in san antonio either project planning or comprehensive planning
aside from the planning directors?
You might start with anyone who's currently on the staff that you're aware of.
Well, how much detail do you want?
Well, I'm talking about senior planner level and that sort of thing.
People who are in charge of various projects or comprehensive plans.
Well, let me just throw out some names over the years and...
some of these people you might want to interview.
